```

Yes, (A) handleLocalResponse runs BEFORE (C) the transition. So applyResponse sees collabBoard status 'in_progress'. The auto-approve check `collabTask.status === 'delivered'` fails. So auto-approve NEVER fires.

For the remote case (B), the response is pushed to Redis stream. On origin, the response consumer runs applyResponse. By that time, the TARGET's collabBoard has transitioned to 'delivered' (C ran on target). But the ORIGIN's collabBoard is separate and never transitioned. So on origin, collabBoard.status is still 'received' (or whatever). The check fails.

So auto-approve is definitively broken in all cases. This is a solid finding.

Actually, the more I think about it, the auto-approve was probably intended to run AFTER the transition, on the origin side, when the origin receives the delivery notification. But the implementation is wrong because:
